  "active_lock_reason": null,
  "body": "Default values for p2p target peer bounds are as follows:\r\n  - p2p-peer-upper-bound: 74\r\n  - p2p-peer-lower-bound: 64\r\n\r\nIf I try to run:\r\n`./teku --p2p-peer-upper-bound=63` or `./teku --p2p-peer-lower-bound=75` (without setting the other parameter) then Teku fails to start with a message:\r\n\r\n```\r\nTeku failed to start.\r\njava.util.concurrent.CompletionException: java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: Invalid target peer count range\r\n        at java.base/java.util.concurrent.CompletableFuture.encodeThrowable(CompletableFuture.java:314)\r\n```\r\n\r\nWe should handle this better. Maybe by setting them equal if only one is specified and is incomaptible with the defaults. For example:\r\n  - If only `--p2p-peer-upper-bound=N` is set and N < 64 (the default lower bound), set the lower bound also to N.\r\n  - If only `--p2p-peer-lower-bound=N` is set and N > 74 (the default upper bound), set the upper bound also to N.\r\n\r\nWhen doing this, output a nice, clear warning message.\r\n\r\nAlternatively, improve the existing error message significantly.",
